e%202015%2C%20its%20budget%20grew%20to%20%242.05%20billion%20by%202022%2C%20a%20scathing%20audit%20report%20said.%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20National%20Aeronautics%20and%20Space%20Administration%20(NASA)%20is%20giving%20up%20its%20mission%20to%20refuel%20old%20satellites%20in%20orbit%2C%20putting%20an%20end%20to%20an%20ambitious%20%242%20billion%20project%20plagued%20by%20delays%20and%20technical%20setbacks.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20administration%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nasa.gov%2Fmissions%2Fupdate-on-status-of-nasas-osam-1-project%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Esaid%20on%20Friday%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20it's%20discontinuing%20the%20effort%20after%20an%20independent%20review%2C%20citing%20%26quot%3Bcontinued%20technical%2C%20cost%2C%20and%20schedule%20challenges.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20On-orbit%20Servicing%2C%20Assembly%2C%20and%20Manufacturing%201%20project%2C%20or%20OSAM-1%2C%20aimed%20to%20build%20a%20robotic%20arm%20that%20could%20top%20up%20satellites%20that%20weren't%20built%20for%20refueling%2C%20thereby%20extending%20their%20lifespan.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BNeed%20extra%20gas%20or%20a%20tune-up%20for%20your%20satellite%3F%26quot%3B%20pitched%20its%20official%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nasa.gov%2Fmission%2Fon-orbit-servicing-assembly-and-manufacturing-1%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ewebpage.%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20development%20since%202015%2C%20it%20was%20supposed%20to%20launch%20in%202025%2C%20but%20this%20was%20delayed%20to%202026.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20OSAM-1's%20refueling%20technique%20seemed%20almost%20like%20brute%20force.%20A%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nasa.gov%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2023%2F02%2Fconops-1.mp4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Econcept%20video%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20robotic%20arm%2C%20called%20the%20Space%20Infrastructure%20Dexterous%20Robot%20or%20SPIDER%2C%20shows%20it%20cutting%20open%20a%20fuel%20hatch%2C%20ripping%20restraints%2C%20and%20unscrewing%20a%20fuel%20cap%20%E2%80%94%20all%20while%20in%20space.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222400%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20SPIDER's%20concept%20video%20shows%20it%20cutting%20away%20a%20fuel%20hatch%20and%20unscrewing%20a%20fuel%20cap.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65e6910290413ab8e1d9203f%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221200%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20SPIDER's%20concept%20video%20shows%20it%20cutting%20away%20a%20fuel%20hatch%20and%20unscrewing%20a%20fuel%20cap.%3Cp%3ENASA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20primary%20objective%20was%20to%20refuel%20the%20Landsat%207%2C%20a%20US%20satellite%20launched%20in%201999%20that%20wasn't%20built%20to%20be%20refueled%20in%20orbit.%20The%20SPIDER%20could%20also%20be%20used%20to%20set%20up%20an%20antenna%20as%20a%20secondary%20function.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20the%20space%20industry%20as%20a%20whole%20has%20been%20pivoting%20toward%20satellites%20already%20built%20with%20refueling%20capabilities%2C%20doing%20away%20with%20the%20need%20for%20such%20a%20device%2C%20NASA%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWith%20fears%20the%20project%20might%20become%20obsolete%2C%20the%20administration%20said%20it%20was%20met%20with%20the%20%26quot%3Black%20of%20a%20committed%20partner.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20of%20the%20contractors%20that%20worked%20with%20NASA%20on%20the%20project%20was%20California-based%20Maxar%20Technologies%2C%20which%20was%20to%20provide%20the%20spacecraft%20and%20robotic%20arm%20under%20contracts%20worth%20%24316%20million.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Foig.nasa.gov%2Fdocs%2FIG-24-002.pdf%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eaudit%20report%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20October%202023%20slammed%20the%20contractor%2C%20saying%20its%20%26quot%3Bpoor%20performance%26quot%3B%20meant%20NASA%20had%20to%20provide%20unplanned%20manpower%20and%20engineering%20support%20to%20help%20it%20deliver.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%2